    HERO ORB RESPONSIVE SCALE
    Problem this solves: the ring/logo graphic on the right side of the
    hero is built from several fixed-pixel circles (760px down to 240px)
-   that never change size. The hero is a 2-column grid (1.2fr text /
-   0.8fr orb), so on a 1920px+ monitor that 0.8fr column is wide enough
-   to hold a 760px circle comfortably — but on a 1366/1440/1536px
-   laptop (or any narrower window) that same column can be 300-500px
-   narrower, so the solid inner rings spill past the edge of the
-   screen and get clipped. This is the "circle is cut off on smaller
-   screens" bug.
-   Fix: wrap the whole ring stack in one box sized to its natural
-   760x760px footprint, then visually scale that whole box down as a
-   single unit at the widths where it would otherwise overflow. Every
-   ring scales together, so their proportions to each other (and to
-   the logo inside) stay exactly as designed — it just gets smaller,
-   like zooming out, instead of breaking.
+   that never change size, sitting in the 0.8fr column of a 2-column
+   grid. Two separate bugs were stacking on top of each other here:
+
+   1) GRID BLOWOUT. A bare `0.8fr` track is really `minmax(auto, 0.8fr)`
+      — its minimum width is the largest min-content size of whatever's
+      inside it. A 760px-fixed-size box (and, on the other side, a
+      whitespace-nowrap label ~850px wide) is exactly that kind of
+      content, so the grid was refusing to shrink either column below
+      its natural size and quietly overflowing the page width, getting
+      clipped by main's overflow-hidden — i.e. the "circle gets cut off
+      at the edge" bug. Fixed in page.tsx via
+      grid-cols-[minmax(0,1.2fr)_minmax(0,0.8fr)] and removing the
+      label's forced nowrap, so the tracks can actually shrink.
+
+   2) WRONG SCALING SIGNAL. Even once the grid can shrink, the old fix
+      here scaled .hero-orb off total *viewport* width via @media — but
+      the orb doesn't get the whole viewport, it gets ~40% of whatever's
+      left after the text column, the gap, and the section's padding.
+      A viewport breakpoint can't know that, so the scale was wrong on
+      exactly the "smaller laptop" sizes being reported.
+      Fix: make the orb's own grid cell a CSS container
+      (.hero-orb-container, set in page.tsx) and scale with @container
+      queries instead of @media — so the orb measures the space it
+      actually has, on any screen, any window width, any sidebar.
    ================================================================ */
+.hero-orb-container {
+  container-type: inline-size;
+  overflow: hidden;
+}
+
 .hero-orb {
   position: relative;
   width: 760px;
@@ -160,31 +176,29 @@ html {
